> My honey-water glaze is quite congealed. Should I heat it up before brushing it on?
**assistant**:
> Yes, if your honey-water glaze has congealed and is not in a pourable consistency, it would be best to gently heat it up before brushing it on the tart. Here's what you can do:
> 
> 1. Transfer the congealed glaze from the small saucepan to a microwave-safe bowl or a small heatproof container.
> 
> 2. Microwave the glaze for a few seconds at a time, stirring in between each interval. This will help melt the glaze and bring it back to a more liquid state. Be cautious not to overheat it, as honey can burn easily.
> 
> 3. Alternatively, you can heat the glaze over low heat on the stovetop, stirring continuously until it reaches a brushable consistency. Again, be mindful not to overheat it.
> 
> 4. Once the glaze is warmed and liquified, you can then brush it over the cooled apple-pear filling in the tart.
> 
> Heating the glaze will restore its fluidity and make it easier to apply. Enjoy finishing up your tart!
